VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'professionals. They allow you to fix ISO, to fix many uh many parameters that are then used in the reconstruction. Someone who comes completely outside from the this this field doesn\'t even know how to fix those parameters. So, we'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we created a perfect setting for the capture, both in terms of how the capture is proceeded, meaning what gesture do you do around the object, but also in terms of the different parameters that we include into that, in'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'terms of the different angles that we get into there. And the standard process allows to make it very easy in the end to replicate and to do multiple times over and over again because it also always the same gesture. And this this has been a lot of bulk of'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the work on the accessibility part, so making it super simple, having a certain capture workflow that is always the same, that is super easy, that is quick. Today our capture workflow takes around a minute and a half to a minute to'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'someone to for someone to do, and that\'s fairly fairly rapid and fairly simple versus other capture workflows that, you know, are are way way longer. And it means also that from our end, we learned to essentially process a video, which is'

[06:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'less easy to process than a multiple set of frames that can be higher quality. We learned to process to cancel effects like blur, like motion blur. We learned to cancel effects like people moving'

